headline: AI Has Pushed the Stock Market to Record Highs. Why the Economy Could Drag It Down.
summary: Investors are getting mixed messages on health of the U.S. economy, leaving stocks in limbo ahead of next week’s Federal Reserve rate decision.  After being powered by the artificial-intelligence trade all year, stocks don’t seem to know where to head this month—traditionally one of the market’s strongest—thanks to data showing solid gains in some corners of the world’s biggest economy, and ongoing weakness in others.  Lower Fed interest rates would almost surely support market valuations over the months ahead.

headline: Heard on the Street Wednesday Recap: Betting on Cuts
summary: The Dow industrials added 0.9% and the Nasdaq composite gained 0.2%.  New data from ADP showed the private sector shed 32,000 jobs in November.  The "modest fall" should be enough to persuade Federal Reserve policymakers to vote for another rate cut next week, said Stephen Brown of Capital Economics.

headline: DLTR Q3 Deep Dive: Multi-Price Strategy Drives Margin Gains Amid Mixed Traffic Trends
summary: Discount treasure-hunt retailer Dollar Tree (NASDAQ:DLTR) announced better-than-expected revenue in Q3 CY2025, but sales fell by 37.2% year on year to $4.75 billion. Guidance for next quarter’s revenue was better than expected at $5.45 billion at the midpoint, 0.6% above analysts’ estimates. Its non-GAAP profit of $1.21 per share was 11.8% above analysts’ consensus estimates.

headline: Dollar General stock surges on Q3 results. So why is still a Hold?
summary: Discount retailer Dollar General (DG) saw its stock surge in Thursday's trading after releasing third quarter earnings, as competitors in the space Dollar Tree (DLTR) and Five Below (FIVE) also got stock lifts after reporting their respective earnings results. Loop Capital Markets Managing Director Anthony Chukumba speaks with Josh Lipton about what he saw in Dollar General's earnings figures and what discount retailers are indicating about the state of the consumer in a K-shaped economy.
